article.description: Chris Whitney scored a season-high 23 points as the Nuggets snapped a five-game losing streak with a 92-81 victory over the Pacers, who have dropped consecutive games for the first time this season.
article.headline: Pacers suffer first loss to team with losing record
article.linkText: Nuggets thwart Pacers' rally, end five-game skid
article.story:
DENVER (AP) -- Chris Whitney and Juwan Howard have talked to their young teammates all season about withstanding opponents' scoring runs.
Howard

Whitney

It paid off against the best team in the Eastern Conference. Whitney scored 23 points, and Howard had 17 points and 10 rebounds as the Denver Nuggets held off the Indiana Pacers 92-81 on Saturday night. The Nuggets played strong early, fought off a third-quarter run by the Pacers, then pulled away late to end a five-game losing streak. ``We tell them, even during games, that teams are going to make runs,'' Whitney said. ``They made their run, but we stayed strong. It shows that we're growing up.'' The Pacers trailed 49-37 at halftime, but went through Jermaine O'Neal to get back in the game. Indiana opened the third quarter by getting the ball to O'Neal in the post nearly every time down the floor. He responded with eight points during a 15-4 run, capping it with a thunderous two-handed dunk that cut Denver's lead to 53-52 with seven minutes left. O'Neal scored 23 of his 26 points in the second half, but it still wasn't enough to keep the Pacers from losing for the third time in four games. ``I just thought that we didn't have any rhythm, we didn't have any energy,'' Pacers coach Isiah Thomas said. ``It seemed like all night we were running in mud.'' Ron Artest gave Indiana its first lead at 56-55 on a scoop shot with 5:58 left, and the Pacers held Denver to 6-for-20 shooting to stay within 67-64 after three quarters. But the comeback seemed to sap all of the Pacers' energy. Denver opened the fourth with a 12-4 run, capped by Donnell Harvey's layup off a give-and-go from Mark Blount. That put the Nuggets up 79-68 with six minutes left, and the lead never dropped below eight from there. Whitney put it away with a 3-pointer off a pick with 2:47 left, telling teammates the game was over as he walked back to the bench. ``It was a good gut-check win for us after a tough week,'' said Nuggets coach Jeff Bzdelik, whose team beat Indiana for just the second time in 14 games. ``The guys kept working, they stayed the course with what we're trying to do and they showed a lot of enthusiasm.'' Thomas worried before the game that his team might be tired and looking forward to going home at the end of a five-game road trip. For good reason. Artest got a technical foul seven seconds in for grabbing and holding Blount's leg, and the Pacers had a couple of sloppy turnovers as Denver opened with a 10-3 run. Indiana didn't have field goal until Al Harrington hit a short jumper 3:21 in, then had just three free throws in the final 4:52 as Denver led 23-17 after one quarter. It didn't get much better for the Pacers in the second. The Pacers made just two shots in the first 4½ minutes and went 5:36 without a field goal midway through. Indiana was 6-for-19 from the field and had a season-low 37 points to trail by 12 at halftime. Brad Miller got so frustrated he had a fragrant foul and a technical foul in the first half. ``We just didn't really come out there ready to play tonight,'' said Miller, who had 15 points and nine rebounds. ``We even said before the game we've got to come out and match it because they come out and play real hard and aggressive. We just didn't match that tonight.'' Reggie Miller, who went scoreless for the first time in 13 years Monday, took just one shot in the first half and had to sit down midway through the third with four fouls. He finished 0-for-4 and had two points. James Posey added 18 points for Denver, which scored more than 90 points for just the third time.

Game notes
Artest seemed to be in a better mood after the early technical, joking with fans in the front row after leaping over them midway through the first quarter. He finished with 19 points... Denver's Nene Hilario played 12 minutes after straining his neck against Sacramento the night before. ... The loudest cheers came when a scoreboard replay showed Colorado's Jeremy Bloom return a punt for a touchdown against Oklahoma in the Big 12 championship game. ... Indiana lost to a team with a losing record for the first time this season (8-1).
